<DOC><DOCNO> AP890905-0134 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1928EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-05 0469</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0479</SECOND><HEAD>Rain, Flooding, Heat and Predictions of Snow</HEAD><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Heavy rains drenched South Carolina on Tuesday, and snow waspredicted in Montana, while the heat index in Texas reached 108degrees.   More than 1\ inches of rain fell at Charleston, S.C., in one hourand 2{ inches had fallen in a six-hour period Tuesday morning.   Three days of heavy rain in northeast Florida had riversapproaching flood levels. Showers and thunderstorms moved acrosscentral Kansas leaving many creeks flooded and roads under waterfrom flash floods. Two and a half feet of water came into some homesat Hackberry Hollow near Arkansas City. Minor flooding continuedalong the Wabash River in central Indiana.   Showers and thunderstorms were reported across much of Floridaand from the central Gulf Coast region to the coastal waters ofTexas, across western Missouri and northeast Oklahoma. Light rainfell th Carolinas and Georgia.   Rough sea conditions prevailed along portions of the East Coast.A heavy surf advisory was in effect on the North Carolina coast.   Sunshine prevailed Tuesday afternoon from the upper Great Lakesacross the Dakotas, Wyoming and the Great Basin area to California.Skies were also sunny over the Tennessee Valley and in much ofTexas. Partly sunny skies were the rule in the northeast.   Afternoon temperatures were in the 70s and 80s across most of thenation. Readings were in the 60s over western portions of theCarolinas and southwest Virginia and much of the north AtlanticCoast.   An excessive heat advisory was in effect Tuesday for parts ofcentral Texas. Waco had a temperature of 98 degrees and a heat indexof about 108 at 3 p.m. EDT.   Southerly winds gusted to over 30 mph from the Great Basin areaacross Wyoming to South Dakota. Aberdeen, S.D., reported a wind gustto 37 mph.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54degrees at Great Falls, Mont., to 110 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstormsscattered along coastal sections of the south Atlantic and Gulfstates and from the northern Rockies across the Dakotas and theupper half of the Mississippi Valley to much of Michigan. Snow wasexpected in the higher elevations of western Montana with gustywinds over portions of Montana and Wyoming.   High temperatures were expected in the 80s and 90s across most ofthe nation. Highs in the 70s were forecast over the North AtlanticCoast, portions of the Great Lakes region, the Pacific Northwest,along the California coast and over the northern intermountainregion. Highs in Montana and northwest Wyoming were expected to bein the 50s and 60s. Temperatures near 100 degrees were expected incentral and southwest Texas and between 100 and 110 in the Southwest.</TEXT></DOC>